posts.subject: Not living right. This is repeated across many industries.
posts.body:
GL250 - Dietz No. 80 Hurricane Lantern

Description

Also known as the "Blizzard", this is the largest and brightest of the original railroad-style hurricane lanterns, so called because the flame is so well protected that even a hurricane will not blow it out.

A while ago Dietz (an American firm) moved all the original tooling to Asia where they continue to make lamps in the same style that first appeared in 1840.

The lantern gives off a 12-candlepower light, burns continuously for up to 26 hours without refuelling and goes out automatically if the lantern tips over. Makes a great emergency light, garden lantern, or nostalgic decoration. A lever lifts the glass globe to expose the wick for quick lighting, extinguishing, or trimming.

>>0b4d2a2d-ce99-4709-a106-4dd8b7f283e4
I was afraid of this. Many things we "know" do not survive statistical tests. 

Ditto all these treatments which do not appear to be accomplishing anything other than padding the patient's bill. Why is it that in NYC 80% of those placed on a ventilator do not survive? Did anyone even question the procedures the Chinese doctors used? Or did all of us launch into ritualized bleeding based upon their dogmas?

It's extremely upsetting how little we know at this late date, and how unreliable our current tests truly are. Very little critical thinking is at work here.

Accordinly, it's way overdue to task multiple independent researchers with investigating this virus. What if everything we think we know is just wrong?

For instance, there was some paramedic (if I find his piece will post) who was arguing that the virus is actually a disease of the blood. Once infected, the patient's blood no longer carries oxygen - so it doesn't matter what you do to preserve the lung's pumping role. That oxygen will never reach organs anyway.

If this guy is right - everyone has been looking for their car keys where the light was better.

It's time for new eyes on this problem.
